In WLS, the mass loss of the MS specimen was determined after dipping in 15 % HCl solution without and with different inhibitor concentration. So, for the WLS, the weight of a mirror polished and cleaned MS specimen was recorded before immersion. The specimen was then immersed in 15 % HCl solution without and with inhibitor for 6 h at different temperatures. After 6 h, specimen was removed from the solution, cleaned with Clarke solution (SnCl2 + Sb2O3) as per ASTM G 1-90 standards, dried and taken the weight. Finely, mass loss was computed and using the mass loss, corrosion rate (
C R
), inhibition capabilities (η%), and the degree of surface coverage (θ) were measured for the MS in 15 % HCl solution.

The electrochemical workstation Corrtest: model CS350 powered by electrochemical and corrosion studio ver. 5.6 was used for electrochemical study. For corrosion study, corrosion cell consisting of MS working electrode, calomel reference electrode and Pt counter electrode was used. The stability of electrochemical system was cheeked via open circuit potential (OCP) experiment. After knowing the stable OCP value, an electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) study was conducted between frequency ranges of 100 kHz to 1 Hz with an AC voltage amplitude of 10 mV. The Nyquist and Bode curves were obtained. The potentiodynamic polarization (Tafel) experiments were carried out at a scan rate of 0.5 mV/s in the potential range of 800 to 200 mV/SCE. The value of corrosion current density (

